title: GRU kernel gate activation functions not updating the zrh buffer

labels.name: core runtime
labels.description: issues related to core runtime

body:
From the cpu GRU kernel:

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/eeef15788804b0217d46ad6d1c2744585ad98d0c/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/rnn/deep_cpu_gru.cc#L917-L919

`p_rt = f(p_rt)` or `p_rt = sigmoid(p_rt)` when f = sigmoid in place.

However, the reset gate implementation:

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/eeef15788804b0217d46ad6d1c2744585ad98d0c/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/rnn/rnn_helpers.cc#L580-L601

Does not seem to be updating the `p_rt` pointer at all. As a result, the zrh pointer does not really represent the true zrh gate computations.

I am wondering if this is a bug or if this was done this way by design.

Context: I am implementing the GRU gradient kernel. The zrh intermediate gate computations are needed to be stashed for gradient computations.

title: Allow ORT actively fallback CUDAExecutionProvider to ROCMExecutionProvider
body:
In the wild, for example, pytorch and huggingface (pytorch pipelines) use `cuda` for amd gpu. Their user can basically painless switch from cuda devices to rocm devices. That is, in pytorch world they fallback cuda to rocm.

When switched to hf ort backend, it will populate a string `CUDAExecutionProvider` automatically to pin down the provider. Then ORT will not play well in this case because the framework will fallback cuda to cpu.

The disparity creates a lot of headache during benchmarking the ROCm EP when reusing scripts for cuda.

This PR address it by allow cuda to fallback to rocm.

body:
### Describe the issue

The `If` operator appears to have a regression in opset 19. I attached two models, one for opset version 18 the other for
 opset version 19. `onnxruntime` 1.15.1 fails to create an `InferenceSession` for the latter with the following error message:
 ```
 onnxruntime.capi.onnxruntime_pybind11_state.NotImplemented: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 9 : NOT_IMPLEMENTED : Could not find an implementation for If(19) node with name 'If_0'
 ```


 It worked as expected for opset version 18.

The issue has been observed on MacOS and Linux.

[models.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/12196600/models.zip)

### To reproduce

Test cases for the regression (using [Spox](https://github.com/Quantco/spox)):
```python
from spox import argument, build, Tensor
import onnx
import onnxruntime as ort
import numpy as np

def test_regression_opset_19():
    import spox.opset.ai.onnx.v19 as op19

    a = argument(Tensor(np.float32, ("N", 1)))
    (c,) = op19.if_(op19.const(True), then_branch=lambda: [a], else_branch=lambda: [a])
    model = build(inputs={"a": a}, outputs={"c": c})

    onnx.save_model(model, "regression_if_opset_19.onnx")

    ort.InferenceSession(model.SerializeToString())  # Fails


def test_opset_18():
    import spox.opset.ai.onnx.v18 as op18

    a = argument(Tensor(np.float32, ("N", 1)))
    (c,) = op18.if_(op18.const(True), then_branch=lambda: [a], else_branch=lambda: [a])
    model = build(inputs={"a": a}, outputs={"c": c})

    onnx.save_model(model, "if_opset_18.onnx")

    ort.InferenceSession(model.SerializeToString())  # Works as expected

```

title: [JS/Common] Fix malformed result of Tensor.fromImage(ImageBitmap)
body:
### Description

Set `canvas` dimensions to the `ImageBitmap` dimensions, thus fixing a malformed Tensor creation.

### Motivation and Context

According to the [HTMLCanvasElement.drawImage() spec](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/canvas.html#drawing-images):
> When the destination rectangle is outside the destination image (the output bitmap), the pixels that land outside the output bitmap are discarded, as if the destination was an infinite canvas whose rendering was clipped to the dimensions of the output bitmap.

meaning that `ImageBitmap` pixels exceeding the canvas dimensions will be discarded. Since no canvas dimensions are set for `Tensor.fromImage(ImageBitmap)` if-case, the default 300x150px canvas dimensions are used leading to the creation of malformed Tensors where all the exceeding pixels are discarded and equal to `0, 0, 0, 0` during the subsequent `pixels2DContext.getImageData()` call.

title: Add WAITPKG checks, add support for TPAUSE in ThreadPool spin
body:
### Description
Adding necessary runtime checks for WAITPKG:
onnxruntime/core/common/cpuid_info.cc
onnxruntime/core/common/cpuid_info.h

Added a spin function with TPAUSE, use it in WorkerLoop if HW has WAITPKG support. Defining the control bit as 0, since this will provide better power savings, but also improve performance of other SMT thread on the same core. See https://www.felixcloutier.com/x86/tpause.
include/onnxruntime/core/common/spin_pause.h
include/onnxruntime/core/platform/EigenNonBlockingThreadPool.h

### Motivation and Context
Change enables TPAUSE support on Alder Lake and newer Intel microarchitectures in the context of Eigen-based threadpool implementation. This allows the CPU to enter light-weight C-state while in a spin, saving power and in this case, improving performance by 3-4%.
See section 'Active Spins in Applications' in
https://cdrdv2-public.intel.com/685865/211112_Hybrid_WP_2_Developing_v1.2.pdf

### Result
Tested with onnxruntime_perf_test.exe on a dynamically quantized model (which I can not share - however these changes are not model specific), running 
`onnxruntime_perf_test.exe -I -m times -r 10000 -o 2 model.onnx`

As to optimal TPAUSE cycle count, testing shows that ~2000 cycles provides the best results. First 2 graphs were generated from onnxruntime_perf_test.exe output, power data collected using Intel Power Gadget on ADL i9-12700H.

- "npm ci" in /js, /js/common and /js/web. this implicitly include:

    - webpack build in /js/common
    - typescript compiler in /js/web

- Prettier formatter (.json, .jsonc, .md)
